#: instructor-training/reference.md:6
msgid "## Books"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:8
msgid ""
"Susan Ambrose et al: *[How Learning Works: Seven Research-Based Principles for Smart Teaching][worldcat-hlw]*.\n"
":   An excellent overview of what we know about education and why we\n"
"    believe it's true, covering everything from cognitive psychology\n"
"    to social factors."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:13
msgid ""
"Stephen D. Brookfield and Stephen Preskill: *[The Discussion Book][worldcat-discussion]*.\n"
":   Describes fifty different ways to get groups talking productively."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:16
msgid ""
"Joshua Foer: *[Moonwalking with Einstein: The Art and Science of Remembering Everything][worldcat-moonwalking]*.\n"
":   Discusses memory techniques within the context of training for the U.S. Memory Championship. Compelling read and\n"
"    also very informative."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:20
msgid ""
"Elizabeth Green: *[Building a Better Teacher][worldcat-babt]*.\n"
":   A well-written look at why educational reforms in the past 50 years have mostly missed the mark,\n"
"    and what we should be doing instead."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:24
msgid ""
"Mark Guzdial: *[Learner-Centered Design of Computing Education: Research on Computing for Everyone][worldcat-lcdce]*.\n"
":   A well-researched investigation of what it means to design computing courses for everyone,\n"
"    not just people who are going to become professional programmers,\n"
"    from one of the leading researchers in CS education."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:29
msgid ""
"Doug Lemov: *[Teach Like a Champion 2.0][worldcat-tlac]*.\n"
":   Presents 62 classroom techniques drawn from intensive study of thousands of hours of video of good teachers in action."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:32
msgid ""
"Therese Huston: *[Teaching What You Don't Know][worldcat-twydk]*.\n"
":   A pointed, funny, and very useful book that explores exactly what the title suggests."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:35
msgid ""
"James Lang: *[Small Teaching][worldcat-small-teaching]*.\n"
":   A short guide to evidence-based teaching practices that can be adopted\n"
"    without requiring large up-front investments of time and money."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:39
msgid ""
"Jane Margolis and Allan Fisher: *[Unlocking the Clubhouse: Women in Computing][worldcat-clubhouse]*.\n"
":   A groundbreaking report on the gender imbalance in computing,\n"
"    and the steps Carnegie-Mellon took to address the problem."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:43
msgid ""
"Claude M. Steele: *[Whistling Vivaldi: How Stereotypes Affect Us and What We Can Do][worldcat-vivaldi]*.\n"
":   Explains and explores stereotype threat and strategies for addressing it."
msgstr ""

# header
#: instructor-training/reference.md:46
msgid "## Papers"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:48
msgid ""
"Baume: \"[Writing and Using Good Learning Outcomes]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/baume-learning-outcomes-2009.pdf)\"\n"
":   A useful detailed guide to constructing useful learning outcomes."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:51
msgid ""
"Borrego and Henderson: \"[Increasing the Use of Evidence-Based Teaching in STEM Higher Education: A Comparison of Eight Change Strategies]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/borrego-henderson-change-strategies-2014.pdf)\"\n"
":   Describes eight approaches to effecting change in STEM education\n"
"    that form a useful framework for thinking about how Software Carpentry and Data Carpentry can change the world."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:55
msgid ""
"Brown and Altadmri: \"[Investigating Novice Programming Mistakes: Educator Beliefs vs Student Data]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/brown-educator-vs-learner-beliefs-2014.pdf)\"\n"
":   Compares teachers' opinions about common programming errors with data from over 100,000 students,\n"
"    and finds only weak consensus amongst teachers and between teachers and data."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:59
msgid ""
"Carroll, Smith-Kerker, Ford, and Mazur-Rimetz: \"[The Minimal Manual](https://doi.org/10.1207/s15327051hci0302_2)\" *Humanâ€“Computer Interaction*, 3:2, 123-153, 1987.\n"
":   Outlines an approach to documentation and instruction\n"
"    in which each lesson is one page long and describes how to accomplish one concrete task.\n"
"    Its focus on immediate application,\n"
"    error recognition and recovery,\n"
"    and reference use after training\n"
"    makes it an interesting model for Software and Data Carpentry."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:67
msgid ""
"Crouch and Mazur: \"[Peer Instruction: Ten Years of Experience and Results]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/crouch-mazur-peer-instruction-ten-years-2001.pdf)\"\n"
":   An early report on peer instruction and its effects in the classroom."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:70
msgid ""
"Deans for Impact: \"[The Science of Learning]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/science-of-learning-2015.pdf)\"\n"
":   Summarizes cognitive science research related to how students learn,\n"
"    and connects it to practical implications for teaching and learning."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:74
msgid ""
"Guzdial: \"[Exploring Hypotheses about Media Computation]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/guzdial-mediacomp-retrospective-2013.pdf)\"\n"
":   A look back on 10 years of media computation research."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:77
msgid ""
"De Bruyckere et al: \"[Urban Myths About Learning and Education]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/de-bruyckere-urban-myths-2015.pdf)\"\n"
":   A one-page summary drawn from their book of the same name."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:80
msgid ""
"Gormally et al: \"[Feedback about Teaching in Higher Ed: Neglected Opportunities to Promote Change]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/gormally-teaching-feedback-2014.pdf)\"\n"
":   Summarizes best practices for providing instructional feedback and recommends specific strategies for sharing instructional expertise."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:83
msgid ""
"Guzdial: \"[Why Programming is Hard to Teach]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/guzdial-why-hard-to-teach-2011.pdf)\"\n"
":   A chapter from\n"
"    *[Making Software][worldcat-making-software]*\n"
"    that explores why programming seems so much harder to teach than\n"
"    some other standard subjects."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:89
msgid ""
"Kirschner et al: \"[Why Minimal Guidance During Instruction Does Not Work: An Analysis of the Failure of Constructivist, Discovery, Problem-Based, Experiential, and Inquiry-Based Teaching]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/kirschner-minimal-guidance-fails-2006.pdf)\"\n"
":   Argues that inquiry-based learning is less effective for novices than guided instruction."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:92
msgid ""
"Lee: \"[What can I do today to create a more inclusive community in CS?]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/lee-create-inclusive-community-2015.pdf)\".\n"
":   A brief, practical guide on exactly that with references to the research literature."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:95
msgid ""
"Mayer and Moreno: \"[Nine Ways to Reduce Cognitive Load in Multimedia Learning]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/mayer-reduce-cognitive-load-2003.pdf)\"\n"
":   Shows how research into how we absorb and process information\n"
"    can be applied to the design of instructional materials."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:99
msgid ""
"Porter et al: \"[Success in Introductory Programming: What Works?]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/porter-what-works-2013.pdf)\"\n"
":   Summarizes the evidence that three techniques---peer instruction, media computation, and pair programming---can\n"
"    significantly improve outcomes in introductory programming courses."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:103
msgid ""
"Wiggins and McTighe: \"[UbD in a Nutshell]({{ page.root }}/files/papers/wiggins-mctighe-ubd-nutshell.pdf)\"\n"
":   A four-page summary of the authors' take on reverse instructional design."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:106
msgid ""
"Wilson et al: \"[Good Enough Practices in Scientific Computing](https://arxiv.org/abs/1609.00037)\".\n"
":   Describes and justifies a minimal set of computing practices that every researcher could and should adopt."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:109
msgid ""
"Wilson et al: \"[Best Practices for Scientific Computing](http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.1001745)\"\n"
":   Describes and justifies the practices that mature scientific software developers ought to use."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/reference.md:112
msgid ""
"Wilson: \"[Software Carpentry: Lessons Learned][swc-lessons-learned]\"\n"
":   Summarizes what we've learned in 17 years of running classes for scientists."
msgstr ""

